      "content": "I've created the documentation file `programming-topics-20251116-121117.md` summarizing our discussion about path aliases.\n\nRegarding your question about `@tests/`:\n\nIn this specific repository (`/Users/datpham/dpmemories/byterover-iam`), `@tests/` does not appear to have any special meaning or configuration. My previous search of the codebase found no references or configurations that would define `@tests/` as a path alias. It seems this project simply uses a `tests/` directory without an alias.\n\nIn other projects, particularly in JavaScript/TypeScript ecosystems, `@tests/` is commonly used as a [path alias](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/module-resolution.html#path-mapping) to refer to a `tests/` directory. This is usually configured in files like `tsconfig.json` (for TypeScript), `jest.config.js` (for Jest), or build tools like Webpack or Babel. The purpose of such an alias is to simplify import paths, making them absolute from a defined root instead of relative (e.g., `import { someUtil } from '@tests/utils';` instead of `import { someUtil } from '../../tests/utils';`).\n\nSince it's not configured here, any attempt to use `@tests/` in an import statement in this project would likely result in a module not found error.",
